Pete Hegseth, Tulsi Gabbard, R.F.K. Jr., and Kash Patel are four MAGA nomin=
ees to the core who don=E2=80=99t have the traditional kinds of r=C3=A9sum=
=C3=A9s and qualifications for the jobs they=E2=80=99re being appointed to.=
 At minimum, you could say they=E2=80=99re controversial. Which of these no=
minees concerns you most about the damage they could do if they were to get=
 confirmed?

Overall, my general concern with those four nominees, and beyond, is that D=
onald Trump and the incoming administration promised to give America the ve=
ry best=E2=80=94the very best economy, the very best border security, and t=
he very best and most talented people to serve this nation. Clearly, the no=
minations that have been put forth have not always met that criteria. We ca=
n do better than the four that you just named.

I=E2=80=99ll lock in on R.F.K. Jr. because he=E2=80=99s the one
individual who I hear the most about when I=E2=80=99m back home in my distr=
ict in Brooklyn or traveling to other districts throughout the country, bec=
ause there=E2=80=99s nothing more precious than the health and well-being o=
f the American people. And to put it into the hands of a known conspiracy t=
heorist who has peddled unfounded conspiracies about a wide variety of issu=
es is clearly problematic, and it=E2=80=99s struck a nerve with many Americ=
ans of every race and region that I=E2=80=99ve encountered over the last fe=
w weeks.

The Soul-Searching Question=E2=80=A6

Where do you find yourself on the spectrum of how much work the Democratic =
Party has to do to fix itself=E2=80=94if it needs fixing at all?

It=E2=80=99s disappointing because we had a goal and objective to win the p=
residency, hold the Senate, and flip the House so we can continue to govern=
 on behalf of the American people, get things done, solve problems in a com=
mon-sense way, and make life better for working-class Americans, middle-cla=
ss Americans, and everyone who aspired to be a part of the middle class. We=
 have to engage in a significant, clear-eyed, candid, comprehensive, and co=
nstructive after-action analysis. If we were to take a step back, it wasn=
=E2=80=99t a landslide at the presidential level; you had seven closely con=
tested battleground states that all swung slightly in one direction, to Don=
ald Trump, which is disappointing.

But
when you have a presidential candidate sweep the battleground states and wi=
n the popular vote, as Trump did, you don=E2=80=99t usually find a situatio=
n where the House will be as close as it=E2=80=99s been for any incoming ma=
jority since 1931=E2=80=A6 How can we possibly say this was a landslide ele=
ction when, based on Trump=E2=80=99s own prior election, he doesn=E2=80=99t=
 match up with the numbers that he produced in the House of Representatives=
? So clearly, the country has said, in what is an evenly divided House, Wor=
k together to solve problems, fix the situation at the border, and lower th=
e price of groceries, gas, childcare, and housing costs. As Democrats, we=
=E2=80=99re prepared to do it. We just hope we can find bipartisanship on t=
he other side of the aisle.

In the current configuration of our world, do you have any plausibly ground=
ed hope that something like a bipartisan coalition government could be in o=
ur near future?

Yeah, I think we=E2=80=99re going to have to find
bipartisan common ground. We=E2=80=99re going to strongly disagree on a lot=
 of issues. And when my Republican colleagues=E2=80=94particularly the far-=
right extremists=E2=80=94go after the rule of law, democracy, our values, r=
eproductive freedom, etcetera, we=E2=80=99re going to strongly defend those=
 things and push back aggressively against them. But I do think we can find=
 common ground, and that=E2=80=99s anchored in my past experience.

In the previous Trump administration, I was proud to be the lead Democrat o=
n the First Step Act, the most consequential criminal justice reform legisl=
ation in a generation. I partnered with Doug Collins, who was the top Repub=
lican on the issue, and we worked with Jared Kushner. Ultimately, the bill =
had strong bipartisan support from Democrats and Republicans, the left to r=
ight, progressives, conservatives, the ACLU and the Koch brothers, the NAAC=
P and the Heritage Foundation, Al Sharpton and Grover Norquist. And it was =
signed
into law by Donald Trump in 2018. If we did it then, we can figure out a wa=
y to make progress on behalf of the American people over the next few years=
=2E

